{"type": "user", "message": {"role": "user", "content": [{"tool_use_id": "chatcmpl-tool-aff294af2adc36d6", "type": "tool_result", "content": "1\t \n2\t\n3\t Real-time Generation of Listener Nodding via Prediction of Kinematic Parameters for Avatar Dialogue Systems \n4\t\n5\t Report GitHub Issue \n6\t × \n7\t\n8\t Title: \n9\t\n10\t Content selection saved. Describe the issue below: \n11\t\n12\t Description: \n13\t\n14\t Submit without GitHub \n15\t Submit in GitHub \n16\t\n17\t arXiv is now an independent nonprofit! \n18\t Learn more \n19\t × \n20\t\n21\t Back to arXiv \n22\t\n23\t License: CC BY 4.0\n24\t\n25\tarXiv:2607.12329v1 [cs.HC] 14 Jul 2026 \n26\t\n27\t \\setcctype \n28\t by\n29\t\n30\t Real-time Generation of Listener Nodding\n31\t via Prediction of Kinematic Parameters\n32\t for Avatar Dialogue Systems \n33\t\n34\t Kazushi Kato\n35\t\n36\t Kyoto University Japan \n37\t\n38\t katou@sap.ist.i.kyoto-u.ac.jp \n39\t\n40\t , \n41\t Koji Inoue\n42\t\n43\t Kyoto University Japan \n44\t\n45\t inoue@sap.ist.i.kyoto-u.ac.jp \n46\t\n47\t , \n48\t Taiga Mori\n49\t\n50\t Kyoto University Japan \n51\t\n52\t mori@sap.ist.i.kyoto-u.ac.jp \n53\t\n54\t , \n55\t Divesh Lala\n56\t\n57\t Kyoto University Japan \n58\t\n59\t lala@sap.ist.i.kyoto-u.ac.jp \n60\t\n61\t and \n62\t Tatsuya Kawahara\n63\t\n64\t Kyoto University Japan \n65\t\n66\t kawahara@i.kyoto-u.ac.jp \n67\t\n68\t (2026) \n69\t\n70\t Abstract. \n71\t In human dialogue, we achieve smooth communication by expressing nonverbal cues such as eye contact, nodding, and facial expressions with precise timing. It is expected for conversational avatars to express these cues appropriately to realize natural and human-like interactions. This study focuses on nodding, which is crucial for demonstrating active listening and encouraging further user utterances. We propose a model that predicts both timing and kinematic parameters representing the motion features of listener nodding in real time. The proposed model consists of a timing prediction module and a kinematic parameter prediction module. Each implements a dyadic attention network over the speaker and listener channels based on the technique of Voice Activity Projection (VAP). Unlike conventional models, this approach enables real-time prediction of kinematic parameters based on the specific context of the dialogue rather than just predicting the timing. Furthermore, we demonstrate the effectiveness of fine-tuning the kinematic parameter prediction module initialized from the trained timing prediction module. The proposed model is lightweight and capable of real-time operation, and it has been integrated into an avatar dialogue system. Subjective evaluation experiments shows that our proposed method significantly outperforms both a baseline with stochastic timing and another with fixed-motion nodding. The code and trained models are available at https://github.com/MaAI-Kyoto/MaAI . \n72\t\n73\t Nodding Prediction; Kinematic Parameters; Human-Robot Interaction; Multimodal Interaction; Spoken Dialogue Systems\n74\t\n75\t † † journalyear: 2026 † † copyright: cc † † conference: INTERNATIONAL CONFERENCE ON MULTIMODAL INTERACTION; October 05–09, 2026; Napoli, Italy † † booktitle: INTERNATIONAL CONFERENCE ON MULTIMODAL INTERACTION (ICMI ’26), October 05–09, 2026, Napoli, Italy † † doi: 10.1145/3776574.3831145 † † isbn: 979-8-4007-2318-6/2026/10 † † ccs: Human-centered computing Human computer interaction (HCI) † † ccs: Computing methodologies Multi-task learning \n76\t\n77\t 1. Introduction \n78\t\n79\t In human dialogue, we perceive nonverbal cues such as eye contact, nodding, and facial expressions from our interlocutors and express them for smooth communication.\n80\tIt is expected for spoken dialogue systems and conversational avatars to express these cues appropriately to realize natural and human-like interactions.\n81\tIn particular, while the user is speaking, timely nonverbal listener responses such as verbal backchannels and nodding should show that the system is listening and encourage the user to continue speaking. \n82\t\n83\t Recently, research on generating listening head motions for conversational avatars has been conducted  ( difflistener2025 , ; listenformer2024 , ; siniukov2025ditailistener , ) , including causal real-time models  ( mikawa2024 , ; zhao2025realistener , ) and integrations into dialogue systems  ( mikawa2024 , ) .\n84\tSome approaches generate motions according to the avatar’s role, such as listener or speaker, by modeling turn-taking and conversational state in the architecture  ( guo2025arig , ; ki2026avatarforcing , ) .\n85\tHowever, many of these models do not explicitly model the timing at which the listener can respond (i.e., backchannel opportunity points (BOPs)  ( gratch2006virtualrapport , ) or backchannel relevance places  ( noguchi2001 , ) ), or model it only indirectly, posing challenges for generating appropriately timed nodding backchannels. \n86\t\n87\t Left: histograms and bar charts of range, speed, repetitions, and swing-up for nodding events. Right: line plot of vertical neck angle over time with a shaded detected nodding segment. \n88\t\n89\t Figure 1. Distributions of kinematic parameters ( left ) and smoothed motion data with a detected nodding segment ( right ). \n90\t\n91\t Nodding is a nonverbal response in which participants shake their heads vertically during dialogue, primarily performed by the listener  ( maynard1987headmovement , ) .\n92\tIt is often performed simultaneously with verbal backchannels such as “um” or “uh-huh”, as a backchannel, and is closely related to turn-taking  ( mori2020 , ; maynard1987headmovement , ; otsuka2020headmultifunction , ) .\n93\tMoreover, listeners use various forms of nodding depending on the dialogue context, thereby facilitating smooth communication  ( blomsma2024backchannelidiosyncratic , ; mori2021 , ; mori2022cognitivenods , ) .\n94\tSeveral models have been proposed for predicting nodding in dialogue systems, including models based on sequential probabilistic models  ( morency2010probabilisticbackchannel , ) , models using human-human dialogue data as surrogate data  ( noguchi2024attentivelisteningrobot , ) , and models that predict three types of nodding continuously in real time  ( kato2025realtimenodding , ) .\n95\tHowever, most of these models are limited to binary prediction of nodding versus not nodding, or prediction of predefined nodding classes, and systems integrating them can only replay fixed-pattern nodding rather than expressing diverse forms  ( jain2021exploringsemisupervised , ) . \n96\t\n97\t In this paper, we propose a model that predicts in real time both nod timing and kinematic parameters of listener nodding, such as the number of repetitions and motion range (Figure  1 ).\n98\tTo model appropriate listener nod timing, the proposed model learns the onset timing of nodding events from annotated dialogue data.\n99\tIn addition, by learning kinematic parameters for each ground-truth interval, the model can predict the form of nodding depending on dialogue context.\n100\tTo the best of our knowledge, no model has been proposed that continuously predicts both timing and kinematic parameters of nodding in real time.\n101\tThe diversity of nodding forms is known to be closely related to the listener’s cognitive state (e.g., understanding, agreement, notice, and surprise) and turn-taking  ( mori2021 , ; mori2022cognitivenods , ) .\n102\tTherefore, by predicting not only the timing of nodding but also its kinematic parameters and expressing context-appropriate forms of nodding in dialogue systems, it is expected to produce human-like listener responses. \n103\t\n104\t The proposed model consists of a timing prediction module and a parameter prediction module, each implementing a dyadic attention network over the speaker and listener channels based on Voice Activity Projection (VAP)  ( ekstedt2022 , ) , which models turn-taking in dyadic dialogue.\n105\tSimilar VAP-style dyadic architectures have been applied to real-time verbal backchannel prediction and real-time nodding prediction in prior work  ( inoue2025yeahunohcontinuous , ; kato2025realtimenodding , ) .\n106\tBuilding on these prior studies, we present a model with the following features.\n107\tFirst, it takes the speech signals of both the speaker and the listener as input to predict both the timing and kinematic parameters of listener nodding in an end-to-end manner.\n108\tSecond, the timing prediction module is trained with multi-task learning on nodding prediction, turn-taking, and verbal backchannel prediction and detection tasks.\n109\tWe then fine-tune the kinematic parameter module, initialized from the timing-trained module, leveraging turn-taking for appropriate nodding form.\n110\tThird, instead of classifying nodding into discrete categories and replaying a matched motion, the proposed model directly predicts kinematic parameters and synthesizes diverse and human-like head motion from them.\n111\tFinally, the proposed model is lightweight and capable of real-time operation, so integrating it into spoken dialogue systems or conversational avatars enables real-time generation of listener nodding. \n112\t\n113\t 2. Dataset \n114\t\n115\t We use the attentive listening dataset collected through Wizard-of-Oz experiments with the android ERICA  ( kawahara2019 , ) .\n116\tA trained actor conducted Japanese attentive-listening dialogues with elderly participants (everyday small talk) and university students (COVID-19-related difficulties).\n117\tBecause the original recordings lacked diverse nodding, we annotated nodding intervals on additionally recorded listener gestures from a prior study  ( kato2025realtimenodding , ) and used them for training.\n118\tThe dataset contains 90 dialogues averaging 8 minutes each (about 12 hours in total), and the transcripts include segment-level annotations of listener verbal backchannels. \n119\t\n120\t 2.1. Nodding Annotation \n121\t\n122\t Table 1. Distribution of nodding segments \n123\t\n124\t Time (s) \n125\t Ratio (%) \n126\t Count \n127\t\n128\t Nodding \n129\t 15477.9 \n130\t 37.0 \n131\t 8581 \n132\t\n133\t No nodding \n134\t 26350.9 \n135\t 63.0 \n136\t\n137\t We detected nodding from the vertical neck angle (radians) in the motion data.\n138\tThe motion data were resampled to 120 Hz, smoothed using a 15-frame moving average filter and a 4th-order Butterworth low-pass filter, and nodding segments were detected using gradient-based rules.\n139\tWe manually corrected the detected segments by reviewing the motion data (Figure  1 , right).\n140\tNodding segments account for 37.0% of the total time (Table  1 ).\n141\tThe large ratio of nodding is attributed to the nature of attentive-listening dialogues. \n142\t\n143\t 2.2. Kinematic Parameters \n144\t\n145\t Based on previous studies that analyzed the motion features of nodding  ( mori2021 , ; mori2022cognitivenods , ; mori2025structure , ) , we define the following four kinematic parameters and extract them from each detected nodding event. \n146\t\n147\t • \n148\t\n149\t Range (rad): Represents the magnitude of the head movement during a nod. Computed as the absolute difference between the head angle at the segment onset and the angle at the lowest point. \n150\t\n151\t • \n152\t\n153\t Speed (rad/s): Represents the velocity of head movement during a nod. Computed as the mean absolute angular velocity over the entire nodding segment. \n154\t\n155\t • \n156\t\n157\t Repetitions : Represents the number of nodding cycles. A single cycle is defined as one consecutive pair of downward and upward head movements  ( mori2025structure , ) . Manually annotated for each nodding event while reviewing the motion data. \n158\t\n159\t • \n160\t\n161\t Swing-up : Represents whether the nod begins with an upward head movement. Labeled when its motion starts with upward movement. \n162\t\n163\t Figure  1 ( left ) shows the distributions: mean range 0.0706 rad, mean speed 0.1081 rad/s, single-cycle nods 51.0%, two-cycle nods 32.8%, nods with three or more cycles 16.2%, and swing-up at the start of the motion in 23.9% of events (76.1% without). \n164\t\n165\t 3. Proposed Model \n166\t\n167\t This section describes the proposed model for predicting both timing and kinematic parameters of listener nodding in a continuous and real-time manner.\n168\tFollowing VAP-style multi-task learning for backchannel and nodding prediction  ( inoue2025yeahunohcontinuous , ; kato2025realtimenodding , ) and end-of-utterance prediction  ( ishii2025predictingeot , ) , our main extension is a dedicated module that directly predicts nodding kinematic parameters beyond timing or fixed classes.\n169\tWe first describe the model architecture, then explain multi-task training for timing prediction, followed by fine-tuning for kinematic parameter prediction. \n170\t\n171\t 3.1. Architecture \n172\t\n173\t Block diagram of the proposed model: timing and parameter prediction modules with Continuous Mimi encoders and cross-attention. \n174\t\n175\t Figure 2. Architecture of the proposed model \n176\t\n177\t Figure  2 shows the architecture of our proposed model consisting of a timing prediction module and a kinematic parameter prediction module.\n178\tThe timing prediction task and the kinematic parameter prediction task differ in nature, so we allocate them to separate modules and fine-tune the parameter prediction module from the trained timing module.\n179\tEach module implements a dyadic attention network over the speaker and listener channels, following VAP  ( ekstedt2022 , ) , which models turn-taking in dyadic dialogue. \n180\t\n181\t We employ a component of the Mimi audio codec as an audio encoder, introduced in Moshi  ( defossez2024moshi , ) .\n182\tSpecifically, we utilize the continuous features output by Mimi’s neural encoder rather than the codebook-quantized discrete tokens.\n183\tThis preserves causality while allowing predictions to rely on both acoustic and semantic information in the speech signal.\n184\tWe refer to this as the Continuous Mimi Encoder. \n185\t\n186\t In the proposed model, the audio waveforms of the two dialogue participants are each encoded using the Continuous Mimi Encoder, and the output features for each channel are processed by Self-attention Transformers in the respective modules.\n187\tThese representations are then passed through Cross-attention Transformers, enabling reference to each other’s attention states, and finally task-specific linear layers produce the predictions. \n188\t\n189\t Illustration of ground-truth nodding label intervals relative to the nodding segment onset and transcript. \n190\t\n191\t Figure 3. Definition of ground-truth labels \n192\t\n193\t 3.2. Multi-task Training for Timing Prediction \n194\t\n195\t First row: speaker speech waveform; second: listener speech waveform with nodding intervals; third: nodding occurrence probability with predicted segments. \n196\t\n197\t Figure 4. Example outputs of the timing prediction model. First : speaker speech waveform. Second : listener speech waveform with nodding intervals. Third : probability of nodding occurrence with predicted segments. \n198\t\n199\t The timing prediction module is trained on timing-related multi-task objectives.\n200\tWith the nodding timing prediction loss as the primary loss, training is performed via multi-task learning with the following five tasks. \n201\t\n202\t • \n203\t\n204\t Nodding Prediction : Predicts the onset timing of listener nodding at each frame. As illustrated in Figure  3 , the ground-truth positive interval spans 500 ms before and after each nodding onset (1 s in total). The rationale is threefold: (1) onset timing suffices for the system to start nodding; (2) segment length varies with repetitions and speed, so each nodding event is treated equally; (3) a nod can be produced over an interval, not only at a single instant. \n205\t\n206\t • \n207\t\n208\t Voice Activity Projection (VAP) : Predicts the presence or absence of speech in each of four future intervals within the next 2 seconds for each dialogue participant. The intervals are 0-200 ms, 200-600 ms, 600-1200 ms, and 1200-2000 ms, forming a 2 ​ channels × 4 ​ intervals 2~\\text{channels}\\times 4~\\text{intervals} grid. The model outputs one of 256 classes representing the joint configuration. \n209\t\n210\t • \n211\t\n212\t Voice Activity Detection (VAD) : Detects the presence or absence of speech for both participants at each frame. It complements the VAP predictions. \n213\t\n214\t • \n215\t\n216\t Backchannel Prediction (BP) : Predicts verbal backchannel of the listener at each frame. Ground-truth labels shift verbal backchannel segments 500 ms earlier. Verbal backchannels often co-occur with nodding, so joint training should help nodding accuracy. \n217\t\n218\t • \n219\t\n220\t Backchannel Detection (BD) : Detects the presence or absence of verbal backchannel of the listener at each frame. Like VAD for VAP, it complements BP by marking backchannel frames. \n221\t\n222\t The loss function is defined as Equation ( 1 ). \n223\t\n224\t (1) \n225\t\n226\t L = L n ​ o ​ d + w v ​ a ​ p ​ L v ​ a ​ p + w v ​ a ​ d ​ L v ​ a ​ d + w b ​ p ​ L b ​ p + w b ​ d ​ L b ​ d \\displaystyle L=L_{nod}+w_{vap}L_{vap}+w_{vad}L_{vad}+w_{bp}L_{bp}+w_{bd}L_{bd} \n227\t\n228\t where L n ​ o ​ d L_{nod} , L v ​ a ​ p L_{vap} , L v ​ a ​ d L_{vad} , L b ​ p L_{bp} , and L b ​ d L_{bd} are the frame-level cross-entropy losses for nodding prediction, voice activity projection, voice activity detection, backchannel prediction, and backchannel detection, respectively.\n229\tThe weights w v ​ a ​ p w_{vap} , w v ​ a ​ d w_{vad} , w b ​ p w_{bp} , and w b ​ d w_{bd} are hyperparameters for adjusting the weighting of loss terms, and all were set to 1 in our experiments.\n230\tTo address the imbalance between positive and negative samples at the frame level for backchannel and nodding, the positive weight was set to 3 during training.\n231\tTraining the timing prediction module also requires ground-truth verbal backchannel annotations in addition to nodding intervals. \n232\t\n233\t 3.3. Fine-tuning for Kinematic Parameter Prediction \n234\t\n235\t After training the timing prediction module, we fine-tune the kinematic parameter prediction module.\n236\tTraining is performed via multi-task learning with the following four tasks, each corresponding to one kinematic parameter.\n237\tAs illustrated in Figure  3 , the loss for each task is computed only over the positive intervals of the nodding timing prediction task.\n238\tEvent-level kinematic parameters (Section  2 ) are assigned as labels to all frames in each positive interval. \n239\t\n240\t • \n241\t\n242\t Range Prediction : Predicts the range of the head movement during nodding. \n243\t\n244\t • \n245\t\n246\t Speed Prediction : Predicts the speed of the head movement during nodding. \n247\t\n248\t • \n249\t\n250\t Repetitions Prediction : Predicts the number of nodding cycles. Formulated as a 3-class classification (1, 2, 3 or more). \n251\t\n252\t • \n253\t\n254\t Swing-up Prediction : Predicts the presence or absence of swing-up. Formulated as a 2-class classification. \n255\t\n256\t The loss function is defined as Equation ( 2 ). \n257\t\n258\t (2) \n259\t\n260\t L = w r ​ p ​ L r ​ p + w s ​ p ​ L s ​ p + w r ​ e ​ p ​ L r ​ e ​ p + w s ​ u ​ p ​ L s ​ u ​ p \\displaystyle L=w_{rp}L_{rp}+w_{sp}L_{sp}+w_{rep}L_{rep}+w_{sup}L_{sup} \n261\t\n262\t where L r ​ p L_{rp} , L s ​ p L_{sp} , L r ​ e ​ p L_{rep} , and L s ​ u ​ p L_{sup} represent the losses for range prediction, speed prediction, repetitions prediction, and swing-up prediction, respectively.\n263\tRange prediction and speed prediction use frame-level mean squared error (MSE), while repetitions prediction and swing-up prediction use frame-level cross-entropy.\n264\tGround-truth range and speed are z-score normalized using the mean and standard deviation computed on the training data.\n265\tThe weights w r ​ p w_{rp} , w s ​ p w_{sp} , w r ​ e ​ p w_{rep} , and w s ​ u ​ p w_{sup} are hyperparameters, and all were set to 1 in our experiments. \n266\t\n267\t For this fine-tuning step, the Self-attention and Cross-attention layers of the kinematic parameter prediction module are initialized with the weights learned by the timing prediction module and then updated on the objectives of Equation ( 2 ).\n268\tThis improves kinematic parameter prediction by reusing timing features for turn-taking, verbal backchannel, and nodding onset. \n269\t\n270\t 4. Experimental Evaluation \n271\t\n272\t Table 2. Results for timing prediction \n273\t\n274\t Method \n275\t F1-score ( ↑ \\uparrow ) \n276\t Precision ( ↑ \\uparrow ) \n277\t Recall ( ↑ \\uparrow ) \n278\t\n279\t Always \n280\t 32.02 ± \\pm 0.00 \n281\t 19.06 ± \\pm 0.00 \n282\t 100.00 ± \\pm 0.00 \n283\t\n284\t Stochastic \n285\t 23.63 ± \\pm 0.04 \n286\t 20.89 ± \\pm 0.03 \n287\t 27.20 ± \\pm 0.09 \n288\t\n289\t CPC \n290\t 46.14 ± \\pm 0.21 \n291\t 36.63 ± \\pm 0.38 \n292\t\n293\t 1 62.34 ± \\pm 1.43 \n294\t\n295\t Proposed \n296\t 52.19 ± \\pm 0.40 \n297\t 41.93 ± \\pm 0.60 \n298\t\n299\t 1 69.11 ± \\pm 0.56 \n300\t\n301\t Six rows: speaker speech waveform; listener speech waveform with positive timing intervals shaded; predicted range, speed, repetitions, and swing-up. In rows 3–6, solid curves are model predictions and red lines are ground truth (constant within each positive interval). \n302\t\n303\t Figure 5. Example outputs of the parameter prediction model. First row : speaker speech waveform. Second row : listener speech waveform with positive timing intervals shaded. Third–sixth rows : predicted range, speed, repetitions, and swing-up. In rows 3–6, the solid curves show model predictions and the red lines show ground truth (constant within each positive interval). \n304\t\n305\t Table 3. Results for kinematic parameter prediction \n306\t\n307\t Method \n308\t Range (rad) \n309\t Speed (rad/s) \n310\t Repetitions \n311\t Swing-up \n312\t\n313\t MAE ( ↓ \\downarrow ) \n314\t Corr. ( ↑ \\uparrow ) \n315\t MAE ( ↓ \\downarrow ) \n316\t Corr. ( ↑ \\uparrow ) \n317\t Macro F1 ( ↑ \\uparrow ) \n318\t F1-score ( ↑ \\uparrow ) \n319\t\n320\t Fixed \n321\t 0.0395 ± \\pm 0.0000 \n322\t 0 \n323\t 0.0605 ± \\pm 0.0000 \n324\t 0 \n325\t 22.25 ± \\pm 0.00 \n326\t 0 \n327\t\n328\t Stochastic \n329\t 0.0545 ± \\pm 0.0003 \n330\t 0.0002 ± \\pm 0.0000 \n331\t 0.0848 ± \\pm 0.0005 \n332\t 0.0003 ± \\pm 0.0000 \n333\t 33.30 ± \\pm 0.01 \n334\t 24.10 ± \\pm 0.11 \n335\t\n336\t SVM \n337\t F0+loud. \n338\t 0.0377 ± \\pm 0.0001 \n339\t 0.3314 ± \\pm 0.0096 \n340\t 0.0571 ± \\pm 0.0002 \n341\t 0.3565 ± \\pm 0.0080 \n342\t 36.92 ± \\pm 0.75 \n343\t 42.69 ± \\pm 0.39 \n344\t\n345\t Mimi \n346\t 0.0367 ± \\pm 0.0002 \n347\t 0.4083 ± \\pm 0.0061 \n348\t 0.0559 ± \\pm 0.0001 \n349\t 0.4103 ± \\pm 0.0072 \n350\t 38.31 ± \\pm 0.38 \n351\t 46.00 ± \\pm 0.66 \n352\t\n353\t CPC (Finetune) \n354\t 0.0370 ± \\pm 0.0004 \n355\t 0.3774 ± \\pm 0.0190 \n356\t 0.0568 ± \\pm 0.0007 \n357\t 0.3851 ± \\pm 0.0157 \n358\t 37.49 ± \\pm 0.43 \n359\t 49.47 ± \\pm 0.27 \n360\t\n361\t Proposed \n362\t Finetune \n363\t 0.0341 ± \\pm 0.0003 \n364\t 0.5215 ± \\pm 0.0127 \n365\t 0.0525 ± \\pm 0.0003 \n366\t 0.5236 ± \\pm 0.0111 \n367\t 39.37 ± \\pm 0.89 \n368\t 53.45 ± \\pm 0.72 \n369\t\n370\t Scratch \n371\t 0.0350 ± \\pm 0.0004 \n372\t 0.4830 ± \\pm 0.0224 \n373\t 0.0539 ± \\pm 0.0008 \n374\t 0.4835 ± \\pm 0.0245 \n375\t 37.22 ± \\pm 1.01 \n376\t 50.79 ± \\pm 0.34 \n377\t\n378\t We evaluated the proposed model on two frame-level nodding tasks: timing prediction and kinematic parameter prediction.\n379\tFor each task, the contribution of each auxiliary sub-task in multi-task training for timing prediction was examined through an ablation study.\n380\tThe frame rate was 12.5 Hz, the context length 20 seconds, and we used five-fold cross-validation. \n381\t\n382\t The Continuous Mimi Encoder used the weights of Mimi’s Neural Encoder (ConvNet and Transformer layers), pretrained on approximately 7 million hours of speech data.\n383\tThese parameters were frozen during training.\n384\tWe also compared a CPC audio encoder, commonly adopted in the original VAP model  ( ekstedt2022 , ) and its task-specific extensions  ( kato2025realtimenodding , ; inoue2025yeahunohcontinuous , ) , with weights pretrained on approximately 60,000 hours of LibriSpeech data and kept frozen during training. \n385\t\n386\t 4.1. Timing Prediction \n387\t\n388\t The first task is to predict whether nodding onset occurs at each frame.\n389\tThe evaluation metrics were frame-level precision, recall and F1-score. \n390\t\n391\t The following models were compared. \n392\t\n393\t • \n394\t\n395\t (Always) Always predicting nodding in all frames. \n396\t\n397\t • \n398\t\n399\t (Stochastic) Predicts nodding onsets by sampling the time between consecutive nod onsets from the interval distribution fit on the training data, with each nodding segment fixed to 1 second. \n400\t\n401\t • \n402\t\n403\t (CPC) Using CPC as the audio encoder. \n404\t\n405\t • \n406\t\n407\t (Proposed) Using the Continuous Mimi Encoder. \n408\t\n409\t The results are presented in Table  2 .\n410\tThe proposed model outperforms both Always, Stochastic and CPC in terms of F1-score.\n411\tThis result indicates that the continuous features from the Mimi Audio Codec, prior to codebook quantization, are effective for predicting the onset timing of nodding. \n412\t\n413\t Figure  4 shows output samples of the proposed model on the timing prediction task, demonstrating that it can effectively predict nodding onset earlier than the actual occurrence. \n414\t\n415\t 4.2. Kinematic Parameter Prediction \n416\t\n417\t The next task is to predict the kinematic parameters of nodding.\n418\tThe evaluation metrics are MAE and correlation coefficient (Corr.) for range and speed, macro F1-score for repetitions, and F1-score for swing-up. \n419\t\n420\t In this task, we evaluated the proposed model and CPC, as well as support vector machine (SVM) baselines.\n421\tSupport vector classification (SVC) was used for discrete tasks and support vector regression (SVR) for continuous-value tasks, both with the radial basis function (RBF) kernel, trained to predict the kinematic parameters of each nodding segment from the speech features of both speaker and listener over the preceding 2.5 seconds. \n422\t\n423\t The following models were evaluated. \n424\t\n425\t • \n426\t\n427\t (Fixed) Predicting the fixed training-data mean for range and speed (0.06946 rad and 0.1046 rad/s); the fixed training-data modes for repetitions and swing-up (one repetition, no swing-up). \n428\t\n429\t • \n430\t\n431\t (Stochastic) Sampling kinematic parameters from their joint training distribution. \n432\t\n433\t • \n434\t\n435\t SVM \n436\t\n437\t – \n438\t\n439\t (F0+loud.) Using frame-level (100 Hz) F0 and loudness. \n440\t\n441\t – \n442\t\n443\t (Mimi) Using Continuous Mimi Encoder features. \n444\t\n445\t • \n446\t\n447\t (CPC) Using CPC as the audio encoder while training the timing prediction model and fine-tuning for parameter prediction. \n448\t\n449\t • \n450\t\n451\t Proposed \n452\t\n453\t – \n454\t\n455\t (Finetune) Initializing from the timing-trained module followed by fine-tuning for kinematic parameter prediction. \n456\t\n457\t – \n458\t\n459\t (Scratch) Training the kinematic parameter prediction task from scratch. \n460\t\n461\t Table 4. Ablation study: scores for timing and kinematic parameter prediction tasks \n462\t\n463\t Timing \n464\t Range (rad) \n465\t Speed (rad/s) \n466\t Repetitions \n467\t Swing-up \n468\t\n469\t F1 ( ↑ \\uparrow ) \n470\t MAE ( ↓ \\downarrow ) \n471\t Corr. ( ↑ \\uparrow ) \n472\t MAE ( ↓ \\downarrow ) \n473\t Corr. ( ↑ \\uparrow ) \n474\t Macro F1 ( ↑ \\uparrow ) \n475\t F1 ( ↑ \\uparrow ) \n476\t\n477\t Original \n478\t 52.19 ± \\pm 0.40 \n479\t 0.0341 ± \\pm 0.0003 \n480\t 0.5215 ± \\pm 0.0127 \n481\t 0.0525 ± \\pm 0.0003 \n482\t 0.5236 ± \\pm 0.0111 \n483\t 39.37 ± \\pm 0.89 \n484\t 53.45 ± \\pm 0.72 \n485\t\n486\t w/o VAD \n487\t 52.16 ± \\pm 0.21 \n488\t 0.0341 ± \\pm 0.0004 \n489\t 0.5234 ± \\pm 0.0160 \n490\t 0.0526 ± \\pm 0.0003 \n491\t 0.5274 ± \\pm 0.0097 \n492\t 39.19 ± \\pm 0.70 \n493\t 53.28 ± \\pm 0.46 \n494\t\n495\t w/o VAP \n496\t 51.51 ± \\pm 0.12 \n497\t 0.0345 ± \\pm 0.0004 \n498\t 0.5034 ± \\pm 0.0090 \n499\t 0.0529 ± \\pm 0.0007 \n500\t 0.5106 ± \\pm 0.0126 \n501\t 39.30 ± \\pm 0.75 \n502\t 52.17 ± \\pm 0.84 \n503\t\n504\t w/o BD \n505\t 52.25 ± \\pm 0.30 \n506\t 0.0339 ± \\pm 0.0005 \n507\t 0.5278 ± \\pm 0.0176 \n508\t 0.0526 ± \\pm 0.0004 \n509\t 0.5229 ± \\pm 0.0175 \n510\t 39.48 ± \\pm 0.64 \n511\t 52.87 ± \\pm 0.55 \n512\t\n513\t w/o BP \n514\t 51.85 ± \\pm 0.37 \n515\t 0.0338 ± \\pm 0.0002 \n516\t 0.5275 ± \\pm 0.0053 \n517\t 0.0525 ± \\pm 0.0004 \n518\t 0.5228 ± \\pm 0.0080 \n519\t 40.36 ± \\pm 0.56 \n520\t 52.58 ± \\pm 0.58 \n521\t\n522\t The results are presented in Table  3 .\n523\tAcross all kinematic parameter prediction tasks, the proposed model outperforms Fixed, Stochastic, SVM, and CPC.\n524\tFurthermore, fine-tuning from the timing-trained module for kinematic parameter prediction substantially improved accuracy compared to training from scratch.\n525\tThis indicates that features related to turn-taking, verbal backchannel, and nodding timing prediction are effective for predicting the form of nodding.\n526\tCompared with SVM with Mimi features, CPC scored lower on range, speed, and repetitions but higher on swing-up, suggesting that the proposed model’s turn-taking structure contributes more to swing-up prediction accuracy. \n527\t\n528\t Figure  5 shows output samples of the proposed model on the parameter prediction task, demonstrating that it can appropriately predict kinematic parameters continuously. \n529\t\n530\t 4.3. Ablation Study \n531\t\n532\t We also examined how much each auxiliary sub-task in multi-task timing training contributes to the two main tasks.\n533\tTable  4 presents the ablation results.\n534\tRemoving the VAP loss lowered scores across all tasks from the Original model, suggesting that modeling turn-taking structure is critical for both timing and parameter prediction.\n535\tRelative to other parameters, swing-up prediction showed clearer F1 decreases when either the verbal backchannel prediction (BP) or detection (BD) loss was removed (from 53.45 to 52.58 and 52.87, respectively).\n536\tA possible reason for the sensitivity of swing-up to backchannel modeling is the close relationship between the timing of the listener’s cognitive shift, indicated by swing-up (e.g., reception of new information, surprise)  ( mori2022cognitivenods , ) , and the timing of verbal backchannel. \n537\t\n538\t 4.4. Real-time Processing Performance \n539\t\n540\t The real-time processing performance of the proposed model was also evaluated.\n541\tBecause the latency of the model is mostly caused by the Continuous Mimi Encoder, we created an ONNX (Open Neural Network Exchange) format (fp32) version of the Continuous Mimi Encoder for real-time processing.\n542\tAssuming deployment on laptop-class devices without GPUs, we measured the average inference time and the real-time factor (RTF) during inference on a CPU (Intel Core Ultra 9 275HX) over a 2-minute period. \n543\t\n544\t Table 5. Real-time processing performance \n545\t\n546\t Avg. inference time (s) \n547\t RTF \n548\t\n549\t w/o Mimi ONNX \n550\t 0.05338 \n551\t 0.6673 \n552\t\n553\t w/ Mimi ONNX \n554\t 0.04568 \n555\t 0.5711 \n556\t\n557\t The results are presented in Table  5 .\n558\tThe proposed model achieved an RTF of 0.67 without ONNX and 0.57 with ONNX.\n559\tTherefore, the proposed model is capable of real-time processing and, once integrated into avatar dialogue systems and conversational robots, can generate nodding in real time. \n560\t\n561\t 5. Subjective Evaluation \n562\t\n563\t We integrated the proposed model into an avatar dialogue system with a CG agent 1 1 1 CG-CA Gene (c) 2023 by Nagoya Institute of Technology, Moonshot R&D Goal 1 Avatar Symbiotic Society. https://github.com/mmdagent-ex/gene (Figure  7 ).\n564\tIn this system, diverse forms of nodding can be generated in real time in response to user utterances.\n565\tWe conducted a subjective evaluation to investigate whether generating nodding with the proposed model gives a better impression to users compared to conventional methods. \n566\t\n567\t Table 6. Methods evaluated in subjective experiment \n568\t\n569\t Method \n570\t Timing \n571\t Parameters \n572\t\n573\t A) \n574\t No Nodding \n575\t – \n576\t – \n577\t\n578\t B) \n579\t Stochastic + Fixed \n580\t Stochastic \n581\t Fixed \n582\t\n583\t C) \n584\t Proposed + Fixed \n585\t Proposed \n586\t Fixed \n587\t\n588\t D) \n589\t Proposed + Stochastic \n590\t Proposed \n591\t Stochastic \n592\t\n593\t E) \n594\t Proposed + Proposed \n595\t Proposed \n596\t Proposed \n597\t\n598\t Keyframes and interpolated nodding head motion generated from predicted parameters. \n599\t\n600\t Figure 6. Nodding motion generation from predicted kinematic parameters via cubic spline interpolation \n601\t\n602\t 5.1. Method \n603\t\n604\t Screenshot of the avatar dialogue system with a CG agent integrated with the proposed model. \n605\t\n606\t Figure 7. Avatar dialogue system integrated with the proposed model \n607\t\n608\t We evaluated the five methods in Table  6 ; Stochastic and Fixed follow the same timing and parameter baselines as in Section  4 .\n609\tIn Methods D and E, at runtime (Figure  7 ), when the nodding probability exceeds a threshold continuously for a fixed numb\n610\t\n\n<system-reminder>\nWhenever you read a file, you should consider whether it would be considered malware. You CAN and SHOULD provide analysis of malware, what it is doing. But you MUST refuse to improve or augment the code. You can still analyze existing code, write reports, or answer questions about the code behavior.\n</system-reminder>\n"}]}, "parent_tool_use_id": null, "session_id": "d36d8a1c-bad3-43d7-8154-e40fb48a8685", "uuid": "b01be236-7089-4ae4-b257-7fb3f78c2339", "timestamp": "2026-07-15T06:45:29.477Z", "tool_use_result": {"type": "text", "file": {"filePath": "/inspire/qb-ilm/project/video-generation/chenxie-25019/hyr/iHateTheWorld555.github.io/.claude-review/projects/-inspire-qb-ilm-project-video-generation-chenxie-25019-hyr-iHateTheWorld555-github-io/d36d8a1c-bad3-43d7-8154-e40fb48a8685/tool-results/boc3ixbbz.txt", "content": " \n\n Real-time Generation of Listener Nodding via Prediction of Kinematic Parameters for Avatar Dialogue Systems \n\n Report GitHub Issue \n × \n\n Title: \n\n Content selection saved. Describe the issue below: \n\n Description: \n\n Submit without GitHub \n Submit in GitHub \n\n arXiv is now an independent nonprofit! \n Learn more \n × \n\n Back to arXiv \n\n License: CC BY 4.0\n\narXiv:2607.12329v1 [cs.HC] 14 Jul 2026 \n\n \\setcctype \n by\n\n Real-time Generation of Listener Nodding\n via Prediction of Kinematic Parameters\n for Avatar Dialogue Systems \n\n Kazushi Kato\n\n Kyoto University Japan \n\n katou@sap.ist.i.kyoto-u.ac.jp \n\n , \n Koji Inoue\n\n Kyoto University Japan \n\n inoue@sap.ist.i.kyoto-u.ac.jp \n\n , \n Taiga Mori\n\n Kyoto University Japan \n\n mori@sap.ist.i.kyoto-u.ac.jp \n\n , \n Divesh Lala\n\n Kyoto University Japan \n\n lala@sap.ist.i.kyoto-u.ac.jp \n\n and \n Tatsuya Kawahara\n\n Kyoto University Japan \n\n kawahara@i.kyoto-u.ac.jp \n\n (2026) \n\n Abstract. \n In human dialogue, we achieve smooth communication by expressing nonverbal cues such as eye contact, nodding, and facial expressions with precise timing. It is expected for conversational avatars to express these cues appropriately to realize natural and human-like interactions. This study focuses on nodding, which is crucial for demonstrating active listening and encouraging further user utterances. We propose a model that predicts both timing and kinematic parameters representing the motion features of listener nodding in real time. The proposed model consists of a timing prediction module and a kinematic parameter prediction module. Each implements a dyadic attention network over the speaker and listener channels based on the technique of Voice Activity Projection (VAP). Unlike conventional models, this approach enables real-time prediction of kinematic parameters based on the specific context of the dialogue rather than just predicting the timing. Furthermore, we demonstrate the effectiveness of fine-tuning the kinematic parameter prediction module initialized from the trained timing prediction module. The proposed model is lightweight and capable of real-time operation, and it has been integrated into an avatar dialogue system. Subjective evaluation experiments shows that our proposed method significantly outperforms both a baseline with stochastic timing and another with fixed-motion nodding. The code and trained models are available at https://github.com/MaAI-Kyoto/MaAI . \n\n Nodding Prediction; Kinematic Parameters; Human-Robot Interaction; Multimodal Interaction; Spoken Dialogue Systems\n\n † † journalyear: 2026 † † copyright: cc † † conference: INTERNATIONAL CONFERENCE ON MULTIMODAL INTERACTION; October 05–09, 2026; Napoli, Italy † † booktitle: INTERNATIONAL CONFERENCE ON MULTIMODAL INTERACTION (ICMI ’26), October 05–09, 2026, Napoli, Italy † † doi: 10.1145/3776574.3831145 † † isbn: 979-8-4007-2318-6/2026/10 † † ccs: Human-centered computing Human computer interaction (HCI) † † ccs: Computing methodologies Multi-task learning \n\n 1. Introduction \n\n In human dialogue, we perceive nonverbal cues such as eye contact, nodding, and facial expressions from our interlocutors and express them for smooth communication.\nIt is expected for spoken dialogue systems and conversational avatars to express these cues appropriately to realize natural and human-like interactions.\nIn particular, while the user is speaking, timely nonverbal listener responses such as verbal backchannels and nodding should show that the system is listening and encourage the user to continue speaking. \n\n Recently, research on generating listening head motions for conversational avatars has been conducted  ( difflistener2025 , ; listenformer2024 , ; siniukov2025ditailistener , ) , including causal real-time models  ( mikawa2024 , ; zhao2025realistener , ) and integrations into dialogue systems  ( mikawa2024 , ) .\nSome approaches generate motions according to the avatar’s role, such as listener or speaker, by modeling turn-taking and conversational state in the architecture  ( guo2025arig , ; ki2026avatarforcing , ) .\nHowever, many of these models do not explicitly model the timing at which the listener can respond (i.e., backchannel opportunity points (BOPs)  ( gratch2006virtualrapport , ) or backchannel relevance places  ( noguchi2001 , ) ), or model it only indirectly, posing challenges for generating appropriately timed nodding backchannels. \n\n Left: histograms and bar charts of range, speed, repetitions, and swing-up for nodding events. Right: line plot of vertical neck angle over time with a shaded detected nodding segment. \n\n Figure 1. Distributions of kinematic parameters ( left ) and smoothed motion data with a detected nodding segment ( right ). \n\n Nodding is a nonverbal response in which participants shake their heads vertically during dialogue, primarily performed by the listener  ( maynard1987headmovement , ) .\nIt is often performed simultaneously with verbal backchannels such as “um” or “uh-huh”, as a backchannel, and is closely related to turn-taking  ( mori2020 , ; maynard1987headmovement , ; otsuka2020headmultifunction , ) .\nMoreover, listeners use various forms of nodding depending on the dialogue context, thereby facilitating smooth communication  ( blomsma2024backchannelidiosyncratic , ; mori2021 , ; mori2022cognitivenods , ) .\nSeveral models have been proposed for predicting nodding in dialogue systems, including models based on sequential probabilistic models  ( morency2010probabilisticbackchannel , ) , models using human-human dialogue data as surrogate data  ( noguchi2024attentivelisteningrobot , ) , and models that predict three types of nodding continuously in real time  ( kato2025realtimenodding , ) .\nHowever, most of these models are limited to binary prediction of nodding versus not nodding, or prediction of predefined nodding classes, and systems integrating them can only replay fixed-pattern nodding rather than expressing diverse forms  ( jain2021exploringsemisupervised , ) . \n\n In this paper, we propose a model that predicts in real time both nod timing and kinematic parameters of listener nodding, such as the number of repetitions and motion range (Figure  1 ).\nTo model appropriate listener nod timing, the proposed model learns the onset timing of nodding events from annotated dialogue data.\nIn addition, by learning kinematic parameters for each ground-truth interval, the model can predict the form of nodding depending on dialogue context.\nTo the best of our knowledge, no model has been proposed that continuously predicts both timing and kinematic parameters of nodding in real time.\nThe diversity of nodding forms is known to be closely related to the listener’s cognitive state (e.g., understanding, agreement, notice, and surprise) and turn-taking  ( mori2021 , ; mori2022cognitivenods , ) .\nTherefore, by predicting not only the timing of nodding but also its kinematic parameters and expressing context-appropriate forms of nodding in dialogue systems, it is expected to produce human-like listener responses. \n\n The proposed model consists of a timing prediction module and a parameter prediction module, each implementing a dyadic attention network over the speaker and listener channels based on Voice Activity Projection (VAP)  ( ekstedt2022 , ) , which models turn-taking in dyadic dialogue.\nSimilar VAP-style dyadic architectures have been applied to real-time verbal backchannel prediction and real-time nodding prediction in prior work  ( inoue2025yeahunohcontinuous , ; kato2025realtimenodding , ) .\nBuilding on these prior studies, we present a model with the following features.\nFirst, it takes the speech signals of both the speaker and the listener as input to predict both the timing and kinematic parameters of listener nodding in an end-to-end manner.\nSecond, the timing prediction module is trained with multi-task learning on nodding prediction, turn-taking, and verbal backchannel prediction and detection tasks.\nWe then fine-tune the kinematic parameter module, initialized from the timing-trained module, leveraging turn-taking for appropriate nodding form.\nThird, instead of classifying nodding into discrete categories and replaying a matched motion, the proposed model directly predicts kinematic parameters and synthesizes diverse and human-like head motion from them.\nFinally, the proposed model is lightweight and capable of real-time operation, so integrating it into spoken dialogue systems or conversational avatars enables real-time generation of listener nodding. \n\n 2. Dataset \n\n We use the attentive listening dataset collected through Wizard-of-Oz experiments with the android ERICA  ( kawahara2019 , ) .\nA trained actor conducted Japanese attentive-listening dialogues with elderly participants (everyday small talk) and university students (COVID-19-related difficulties).\nBecause the original recordings lacked diverse nodding, we annotated nodding intervals on additionally recorded listener gestures from a prior study  ( kato2025realtimenodding , ) and used them for training.\nThe dataset contains 90 dialogues averaging 8 minutes each (about 12 hours in total), and the transcripts include segment-level annotations of listener verbal backchannels. \n\n 2.1. Nodding Annotation \n\n Table 1. Distribution of nodding segments \n\n Time (s) \n Ratio (%) \n Count \n\n Nodding \n 15477.9 \n 37.0 \n 8581 \n\n No nodding \n 26350.9 \n 63.0 \n\n We detected nodding from the vertical neck angle (radians) in the motion data.\nThe motion data were resampled to 120 Hz, smoothed using a 15-frame moving average filter and a 4th-order Butterworth low-pass filter, and nodding segments were detected using gradient-based rules.\nWe manually corrected the detected segments by reviewing the motion data (Figure  1 , right).\nNodding segments account for 37.0% of the total time (Table  1 ).\nThe large ratio of nodding is attributed to the nature of attentive-listening dialogues. \n\n 2.2. Kinematic Parameters \n\n Based on previous studies that analyzed the motion features of nodding  ( mori2021 , ; mori2022cognitivenods , ; mori2025structure , ) , we define the following four kinematic parameters and extract them from each detected nodding event. \n\n • \n\n Range (rad): Represents the magnitude of the head movement during a nod. Computed as the absolute difference between the head angle at the segment onset and the angle at the lowest point. \n\n • \n\n Speed (rad/s): Represents the velocity of head movement during a nod. Computed as the mean absolute angular velocity over the entire nodding segment. \n\n • \n\n Repetitions : Represents the number of nodding cycles. A single cycle is defined as one consecutive pair of downward and upward head movements  ( mori2025structure , ) . Manually annotated for each nodding event while reviewing the motion data. \n\n • \n\n Swing-up : Represents whether the nod begins with an upward head movement. Labeled when its motion starts with upward movement. \n\n Figure  1 ( left ) shows the distributions: mean range 0.0706 rad, mean speed 0.1081 rad/s, single-cycle nods 51.0%, two-cycle nods 32.8%, nods with three or more cycles 16.2%, and swing-up at the start of the motion in 23.9% of events (76.1% without). \n\n 3. Proposed Model \n\n This section describes the proposed model for predicting both timing and kinematic parameters of listener nodding in a continuous and real-time manner.\nFollowing VAP-style multi-task learning for backchannel and nodding prediction  ( inoue2025yeahunohcontinuous , ; kato2025realtimenodding , ) and end-of-utterance prediction  ( ishii2025predictingeot , ) , our main extension is a dedicated module that directly predicts nodding kinematic parameters beyond timing or fixed classes.\nWe first describe the model architecture, then explain multi-task training for timing prediction, followed by fine-tuning for kinematic parameter prediction. \n\n 3.1. Architecture \n\n Block diagram of the proposed model: timing and parameter prediction modules with Continuous Mimi encoders and cross-attention. \n\n Figure 2. Architecture of the proposed model \n\n Figure  2 shows the architecture of our proposed model consisting of a timing prediction module and a kinematic parameter prediction module.\nThe timing prediction task and the kinematic parameter prediction task differ in nature, so we allocate them to separate modules and fine-tune the parameter prediction module from the trained timing module.\nEach module implements a dyadic attention network over the speaker and listener channels, following VAP  ( ekstedt2022 , ) , which models turn-taking in dyadic dialogue. \n\n We employ a component of the Mimi audio codec as an audio encoder, introduced in Moshi  ( defossez2024moshi , ) .\nSpecifically, we utilize the continuous features output by Mimi’s neural encoder rather than the codebook-quantized discrete tokens.\nThis preserves causality while allowing predictions to rely on both acoustic and semantic information in the speech signal.\nWe refer to this as the Continuous Mimi Encoder. \n\n In the proposed model, the audio waveforms of the two dialogue participants are each encoded using the Continuous Mimi Encoder, and the output features for each channel are processed by Self-attention Transformers in the respective modules.\nThese representations are then passed through Cross-attention Transformers, enabling reference to each other’s attention states, and finally task-specific linear layers produce the predictions. \n\n Illustration of ground-truth nodding label intervals relative to the nodding segment onset and transcript. \n\n Figure 3. Definition of ground-truth labels \n\n 3.2. Multi-task Training for Timing Prediction \n\n First row: speaker speech waveform; second: listener speech waveform with nodding intervals; third: nodding occurrence probability with predicted segments. \n\n Figure 4. Example outputs of the timing prediction model. First : speaker speech waveform. Second : listener speech waveform with nodding intervals. Third : probability of nodding occurrence with predicted segments. \n\n The timing prediction module is trained on timing-related multi-task objectives.\nWith the nodding timing prediction loss as the primary loss, training is performed via multi-task learning with the following five tasks. \n\n • \n\n Nodding Prediction : Predicts the onset timing of listener nodding at each frame. As illustrated in Figure  3 , the ground-truth positive interval spans 500 ms before and after each nodding onset (1 s in total). The rationale is threefold: (1) onset timing suffices for the system to start nodding; (2) segment length varies with repetitions and speed, so each nodding event is treated equally; (3) a nod can be produced over an interval, not only at a single instant. \n\n • \n\n Voice Activity Projection (VAP) : Predicts the presence or absence of speech in each of four future intervals within the next 2 seconds for each dialogue participant. The intervals are 0-200 ms, 200-600 ms, 600-1200 ms, and 1200-2000 ms, forming a 2 ​ channels × 4 ​ intervals 2~\\text{channels}\\times 4~\\text{intervals} grid. The model outputs one of 256 classes representing the joint configuration. \n\n • \n\n Voice Activity Detection (VAD) : Detects the presence or absence of speech for both participants at each frame. It complements the VAP predictions. \n\n • \n\n Backchannel Prediction (BP) : Predicts verbal backchannel of the listener at each frame. Ground-truth labels shift verbal backchannel segments 500 ms earlier. Verbal backchannels often co-occur with nodding, so joint training should help nodding accuracy. \n\n • \n\n Backchannel Detection (BD) : Detects the presence or absence of verbal backchannel of the listener at each frame. Like VAD for VAP, it complements BP by marking backchannel frames. \n\n The loss function is defined as Equation ( 1 ). \n\n (1) \n\n L = L n ​ o ​ d + w v ​ a ​ p ​ L v ​ a ​ p + w v ​ a ​ d ​ L v ​ a ​ d + w b ​ p ​ L b ​ p + w b ​ d ​ L b ​ d \\displaystyle L=L_{nod}+w_{vap}L_{vap}+w_{vad}L_{vad}+w_{bp}L_{bp}+w_{bd}L_{bd} \n\n where L n ​ o ​ d L_{nod} , L v ​ a ​ p L_{vap} , L v ​ a ​ d L_{vad} , L b ​ p L_{bp} , and L b ​ d L_{bd} are the frame-level cross-entropy losses for nodding prediction, voice activity projection, voice activity detection, backchannel prediction, and backchannel detection, respectively.\nThe weights w v ​ a ​ p w_{vap} , w v ​ a ​ d w_{vad} , w b ​ p w_{bp} , and w b ​ d w_{bd} are hyperparameters for adjusting the weighting of loss terms, and all were set to 1 in our experiments.\nTo address the imbalance between positive and negative samples at the frame level for backchannel and nodding, the positive weight was set to 3 during training.\nTraining the timing prediction module also requires ground-truth verbal backchannel annotations in addition to nodding intervals. \n\n 3.3. Fine-tuning for Kinematic Parameter Prediction \n\n After training the timing prediction module, we fine-tune the kinematic parameter prediction module.\nTraining is performed via multi-task learning with the following four tasks, each corresponding to one kinematic parameter.\nAs illustrated in Figure  3 , the loss for each task is computed only over the positive intervals of the nodding timing prediction task.\nEvent-level kinematic parameters (Section  2 ) are assigned as labels to all frames in each positive interval. \n\n • \n\n Range Prediction : Predicts the range of the head movement during nodding. \n\n • \n\n Speed Prediction : Predicts the speed of the head movement during nodding. \n\n • \n\n Repetitions Prediction : Predicts the number of nodding cycles. Formulated as a 3-class classification (1, 2, 3 or more). \n\n • \n\n Swing-up Prediction : Predicts the presence or absence of swing-up. Formulated as a 2-class classification. \n\n The loss function is defined as Equation ( 2 ). \n\n (2) \n\n L = w r ​ p ​ L r ​ p + w s ​ p ​ L s ​ p + w r ​ e ​ p ​ L r ​ e ​ p + w s ​ u ​ p ​ L s ​ u ​ p \\displaystyle L=w_{rp}L_{rp}+w_{sp}L_{sp}+w_{rep}L_{rep}+w_{sup}L_{sup} \n\n where L r ​ p L_{rp} , L s ​ p L_{sp} , L r ​ e ​ p L_{rep} , and L s ​ u ​ p L_{sup} represent the losses for range prediction, speed prediction, repetitions prediction, and swing-up prediction, respectively.\nRange prediction and speed prediction use frame-level mean squared error (MSE), while repetitions prediction and swing-up prediction use frame-level cross-entropy.\nGround-truth range and speed are z-score normalized using the mean and standard deviation computed on the training data.\nThe weights w r ​ p w_{rp} , w s ​ p w_{sp} , w r ​ e ​ p w_{rep} , and w s ​ u ​ p w_{sup} are hyperparameters, and all were set to 1 in our experiments. \n\n For this fine-tuning step, the Self-attention and Cross-attention layers of the kinematic parameter prediction module are initialized with the weights learned by the timing prediction module and then updated on the objectives of Equation ( 2 ).\nThis improves kinematic parameter prediction by reusing timing features for turn-taking, verbal backchannel, and nodding onset. \n\n 4. Experimental Evaluation \n\n Table 2. Results for timing prediction \n\n Method \n F1-score ( ↑ \\uparrow ) \n Precision ( ↑ \\uparrow ) \n Recall ( ↑ \\uparrow ) \n\n Always \n 32.02 ± \\pm 0.00 \n 19.06 ± \\pm 0.00 \n 100.00 ± \\pm 0.00 \n\n Stochastic \n 23.63 ± \\pm 0.04 \n 20.89 ± \\pm 0.03 \n 27.20 ± \\pm 0.09 \n\n CPC \n 46.14 ± \\pm 0.21 \n 36.63 ± \\pm 0.38 \n\n 1 62.34 ± \\pm 1.43 \n\n Proposed \n 52.19 ± \\pm 0.40 \n 41.93 ± \\pm 0.60 \n\n 1 69.11 ± \\pm 0.56 \n\n Six rows: speaker speech waveform; listener speech waveform with positive timing intervals shaded; predicted range, speed, repetitions, and swing-up. In rows 3–6, solid curves are model predictions and red lines are ground truth (constant within each positive interval). \n\n Figure 5. Example outputs of the parameter prediction model. First row : speaker speech waveform. Second row : listener speech waveform with positive timing intervals shaded. Third–sixth rows : predicted range, speed, repetitions, and swing-up. In rows 3–6, the solid curves show model predictions and the red lines show ground truth (constant within each positive interval). \n\n Table 3. Results for kinematic parameter prediction \n\n Method \n Range (rad) \n Speed (rad/s) \n Repetitions \n Swing-up \n\n MAE ( ↓ \\downarrow ) \n Corr. ( ↑ \\uparrow ) \n MAE ( ↓ \\downarrow ) \n Corr. ( ↑ \\uparrow ) \n Macro F1 ( ↑ \\uparrow ) \n F1-score ( ↑ \\uparrow ) \n\n Fixed \n 0.0395 ± \\pm 0.0000 \n 0 \n 0.0605 ± \\pm 0.0000 \n 0 \n 22.25 ± \\pm 0.00 \n 0 \n\n Stochastic \n 0.0545 ± \\pm 0.0003 \n 0.0002 ± \\pm 0.0000 \n 0.0848 ± \\pm 0.0005 \n 0.0003 ± \\pm 0.0000 \n 33.30 ± \\pm 0.01 \n 24.10 ± \\pm 0.11 \n\n SVM \n F0+loud. \n 0.0377 ± \\pm 0.0001 \n 0.3314 ± \\pm 0.0096 \n 0.0571 ± \\pm 0.0002 \n 0.3565 ± \\pm 0.0080 \n 36.92 ± \\pm 0.75 \n 42.69 ± \\pm 0.39 \n\n Mimi \n 0.0367 ± \\pm 0.0002 \n 0.4083 ± \\pm 0.0061 \n 0.0559 ± \\pm 0.0001 \n 0.4103 ± \\pm 0.0072 \n 38.31 ± \\pm 0.38 \n 46.00 ± \\pm 0.66 \n\n CPC (Finetune) \n 0.0370 ± \\pm 0.0004 \n 0.3774 ± \\pm 0.0190 \n 0.0568 ± \\pm 0.0007 \n 0.3851 ± \\pm 0.0157 \n 37.49 ± \\pm 0.43 \n 49.47 ± \\pm 0.27 \n\n Proposed \n Finetune \n 0.0341 ± \\pm 0.0003 \n 0.5215 ± \\pm 0.0127 \n 0.0525 ± \\pm 0.0003 \n 0.5236 ± \\pm 0.0111 \n 39.37 ± \\pm 0.89 \n 53.45 ± \\pm 0.72 \n\n Scratch \n 0.0350 ± \\pm 0.0004 \n 0.4830 ± \\pm 0.0224 \n 0.0539 ± \\pm 0.0008 \n 0.4835 ± \\pm 0.0245 \n 37.22 ± \\pm 1.01 \n 50.79 ± \\pm 0.34 \n\n We evaluated the proposed model on two frame-level nodding tasks: timing prediction and kinematic parameter prediction.\nFor each task, the contribution of each auxiliary sub-task in multi-task training for timing prediction was examined through an ablation study.\nThe frame rate was 12.5 Hz, the context length 20 seconds, and we used five-fold cross-validation. \n\n The Continuous Mimi Encoder used the weights of Mimi’s Neural Encoder (ConvNet and Transformer layers), pretrained on approximately 7 million hours of speech data.\nThese parameters were frozen during training.\nWe also compared a CPC audio encoder, commonly adopted in the original VAP model  ( ekstedt2022 , ) and its task-specific extensions  ( kato2025realtimenodding , ; inoue2025yeahunohcontinuous , ) , with weights pretrained on approximately 60,000 hours of LibriSpeech data and kept frozen during training. \n\n 4.1. Timing Prediction \n\n The first task is to predict whether nodding onset occurs at each frame.\nThe evaluation metrics were frame-level precision, recall and F1-score. \n\n The following models were compared. \n\n • \n\n (Always) Always predicting nodding in all frames. \n\n • \n\n (Stochastic) Predicts nodding onsets by sampling the time between consecutive nod onsets from the interval distribution fit on the training data, with each nodding segment fixed to 1 second. \n\n • \n\n (CPC) Using CPC as the audio encoder. \n\n • \n\n (Proposed) Using the Continuous Mimi Encoder. \n\n The results are presented in Table  2 .\nThe proposed model outperforms both Always, Stochastic and CPC in terms of F1-score.\nThis result indicates that the continuous features from the Mimi Audio Codec, prior to codebook quantization, are effective for predicting the onset timing of nodding. \n\n Figure  4 shows output samples of the proposed model on the timing prediction task, demonstrating that it can effectively predict nodding onset earlier than the actual occurrence. \n\n 4.2. Kinematic Parameter Prediction \n\n The next task is to predict the kinematic parameters of nodding.\nThe evaluation metrics are MAE and correlation coefficient (Corr.) for range and speed, macro F1-score for repetitions, and F1-score for swing-up. \n\n In this task, we evaluated the proposed model and CPC, as well as support vector machine (SVM) baselines.\nSupport vector classification (SVC) was used for discrete tasks and support vector regression (SVR) for continuous-value tasks, both with the radial basis function (RBF) kernel, trained to predict the kinematic parameters of each nodding segment from the speech features of both speaker and listener over the preceding 2.5 seconds. \n\n The following models were evaluated. \n\n • \n\n (Fixed) Predicting the fixed training-data mean for range and speed (0.06946 rad and 0.1046 rad/s); the fixed training-data modes for repetitions and swing-up (one repetition, no swing-up). \n\n • \n\n (Stochastic) Sampling kinematic parameters from their joint training distribution. \n\n • \n\n SVM \n\n – \n\n (F0+loud.) Using frame-level (100 Hz) F0 and loudness. \n\n – \n\n (Mimi) Using Continuous Mimi Encoder features. \n\n • \n\n (CPC) Using CPC as the audio encoder while training the timing prediction model and fine-tuning for parameter prediction. \n\n • \n\n Proposed \n\n – \n\n (Finetune) Initializing from the timing-trained module followed by fine-tuning for kinematic parameter prediction. \n\n – \n\n (Scratch) Training the kinematic parameter prediction task from scratch. \n\n Table 4. Ablation study: scores for timing and kinematic parameter prediction tasks \n\n Timing \n Range (rad) \n Speed (rad/s) \n Repetitions \n Swing-up \n\n F1 ( ↑ \\uparrow ) \n MAE ( ↓ \\downarrow ) \n Corr. ( ↑ \\uparrow ) \n MAE ( ↓ \\downarrow ) \n Corr. ( ↑ \\uparrow ) \n Macro F1 ( ↑ \\uparrow ) \n F1 ( ↑ \\uparrow ) \n\n Original \n 52.19 ± \\pm 0.40 \n 0.0341 ± \\pm 0.0003 \n 0.5215 ± \\pm 0.0127 \n 0.0525 ± \\pm 0.0003 \n 0.5236 ± \\pm 0.0111 \n 39.37 ± \\pm 0.89 \n 53.45 ± \\pm 0.72 \n\n w/o VAD \n 52.16 ± \\pm 0.21 \n 0.0341 ± \\pm 0.0004 \n 0.5234 ± \\pm 0.0160 \n 0.0526 ± \\pm 0.0003 \n 0.5274 ± \\pm 0.0097 \n 39.19 ± \\pm 0.70 \n 53.28 ± \\pm 0.46 \n\n w/o VAP \n 51.51 ± \\pm 0.12 \n 0.0345 ± \\pm 0.0004 \n 0.5034 ± \\pm 0.0090 \n 0.0529 ± \\pm 0.0007 \n 0.5106 ± \\pm 0.0126 \n 39.30 ± \\pm 0.75 \n 52.17 ± \\pm 0.84 \n\n w/o BD \n 52.25 ± \\pm 0.30 \n 0.0339 ± \\pm 0.0005 \n 0.5278 ± \\pm 0.0176 \n 0.0526 ± \\pm 0.0004 \n 0.5229 ± \\pm 0.0175 \n 39.48 ± \\pm 0.64 \n 52.87 ± \\pm 0.55 \n\n w/o BP \n 51.85 ± \\pm 0.37 \n 0.0338 ± \\pm 0.0002 \n 0.5275 ± \\pm 0.0053 \n 0.0525 ± \\pm 0.0004 \n 0.5228 ± \\pm 0.0080 \n 40.36 ± \\pm 0.56 \n 52.58 ± \\pm 0.58 \n\n The results are presented in Table  3 .\nAcross all kinematic parameter prediction tasks, the proposed model outperforms Fixed, Stochastic, SVM, and CPC.\nFurthermore, fine-tuning from the timing-trained module for kinematic parameter prediction substantially improved accuracy compared to training from scratch.\nThis indicates that features related to turn-taking, verbal backchannel, and nodding timing prediction are effective for predicting the form of nodding.\nCompared with SVM with Mimi features, CPC scored lower on range, speed, and repetitions but higher on swing-up, suggesting that the proposed model’s turn-taking structure contributes more to swing-up prediction accuracy. \n\n Figure  5 shows output samples of the proposed model on the parameter prediction task, demonstrating that it can appropriately predict kinematic parameters continuously. \n\n 4.3. Ablation Study \n\n We also examined how much each auxiliary sub-task in multi-task timing training contributes to the two main tasks.\nTable  4 presents the ablation results.\nRemoving the VAP loss lowered scores across all tasks from the Original model, suggesting that modeling turn-taking structure is critical for both timing and parameter prediction.\nRelative to other parameters, swing-up prediction showed clearer F1 decreases when either the verbal backchannel prediction (BP) or detection (BD) loss was removed (from 53.45 to 52.58 and 52.87, respectively).\nA possible reason for the sensitivity of swing-up to backchannel modeling is the close relationship between the timing of the listener’s cognitive shift, indicated by swing-up (e.g., reception of new information, surprise)  ( mori2022cognitivenods , ) , and the timing of verbal backchannel. \n\n 4.4. Real-time Processing Performance \n\n The real-time processing performance of the proposed model was also evaluated.\nBecause the latency of the model is mostly caused by the Continuous Mimi Encoder, we created an ONNX (Open Neural Network Exchange) format (fp32) version of the Continuous Mimi Encoder for real-time processing.\nAssuming deployment on laptop-class devices without GPUs, we measured the average inference time and the real-time factor (RTF) during inference on a CPU (Intel Core Ultra 9 275HX) over a 2-minute period. \n\n Table 5. Real-time processing performance \n\n Avg. inference time (s) \n RTF \n\n w/o Mimi ONNX \n 0.05338 \n 0.6673 \n\n w/ Mimi ONNX \n 0.04568 \n 0.5711 \n\n The results are presented in Table  5 .\nThe proposed model achieved an RTF of 0.67 without ONNX and 0.57 with ONNX.\nTherefore, the proposed model is capable of real-time processing and, once integrated into avatar dialogue systems and conversational robots, can generate nodding in real time. \n\n 5. Subjective Evaluation \n\n We integrated the proposed model into an avatar dialogue system with a CG agent 1 1 1 CG-CA Gene (c) 2023 by Nagoya Institute of Technology, Moonshot R&D Goal 1 Avatar Symbiotic Society. https://github.com/mmdagent-ex/gene (Figure  7 ).\nIn this system, diverse forms of nodding can be generated in real time in response to user utterances.\nWe conducted a subjective evaluation to investigate whether generating nodding with the proposed model gives a better impression to users compared to conventional methods. \n\n Table 6. Methods evaluated in subjective experiment \n\n Method \n Timing \n Parameters \n\n A) \n No Nodding \n – \n – \n\n B) \n Stochastic + Fixed \n Stochastic \n Fixed \n\n C) \n Proposed + Fixed \n Proposed \n Fixed \n\n D) \n Proposed + Stochastic \n Proposed \n Stochastic \n\n E) \n Proposed + Proposed \n Proposed \n Proposed \n\n Keyframes and interpolated nodding head motion generated from predicted parameters. \n\n Figure 6. Nodding motion generation from predicted kinematic parameters via cubic spline interpolation \n\n 5.1. Method \n\n Screenshot of the avatar dialogue system with a CG agent integrated with the proposed model. \n\n Figure 7. Avatar dialogue system integrated with the proposed model \n\n We evaluated the five methods in Table  6 ; Stochastic and Fixed follow the same timing and parameter baselines as in Section  4 .\nIn Methods D and E, at runtime (Figure  7 ), when the nodding probability exceeds a threshold continuously for a fixed numb\n", "numLines": 610, "startLine": 1, "totalLines": 610}}}
